We were on a staycation in Waikiki and wanted Thai. Having serious reservations on eating Thai (i’m thai) believing it would cater to tourists and not be authentic, I took a chance anyways. I’m glad I did. Considering we are in a pandemic, the restaurant was pretty busy but socially distanced. We decided to do take-out and waited outside for our order. The lady who took our order was also the one waitress. She was super busy but efficient. I ordered panang with tofu $14, medium spice. It was a large portion, delicious and spicy but not too spicy. My kid had the ginger chicken $14. She ordered without mushrooms. This was prepared much different than what she is used to (chicken and long beans) but having tried theirs, stated it was the only way she’d eat bell peppers. That speaks volumes as she doesn’t like them. Flavors were very good and not overpowering. We also ordered sticky rice $2.50. Their portions are big for takeout and I had leftovers for 3 days. Sticky rice was also generous. I definitely would come here again. It’s true not to judge a book by it’s cover. It’s located upstairs and I would never have seen it just passing by. Not sure where I’d park if I drove (walked from our hotel) so would assume street parking. Give them a chance. A little pricey but definitely delicious.

Food was great, place was busy, although cramped and loud. Had Tom Yum soup and it was hot and the soup was delicious. There were 5 of us in my family eating, my two teenage sons, 22 year old daughter and my husband and myself. Ordering was easy and the food took about 15-18 minutes to come to the table which I felt was reasonable. There were 4 or 5 females attending all of the tables sharing in the many responsibilities. No one waitress waited on us, as they all came to the table at different times. After we had placed our order, I began smelling a foul odor that seemed like a filthy dog odor mixed with foot odor of someone wearing the same shoes and socks for weeks, I can’t describe it any better and I’m sorry. It was foul and it stayed for a good 10 minutes and my husband and son commented that something was terribly sour or dirty... I told one waitress and she just nodded her head and never came back to address it. We sensed it slightly less through the meal, not knowing if it were olfactory fatigue or if it was truly dissipating. We received our check which had a red stamp with words “15% gratuity is recommended”.  The bill had the items’ amounts listed and one 4% under the top half sum and then 15% listed on the lower half, neither percentage explained, with it all added to the final sum. When we went to the counter register to pay, I asked if the gratuity for the 5 of us were automatically added and the waitress said yes. I asked if this is what is done for each customer and she said yes, for everyone. The credit card receipt she asked me to sign had a line for additional gratuity to be added. I take issue with adding the gratuity and then putting the statement in red on the bill seemingly suggesting the customer pay another 15% of the total without stating anywhere that the gratuity is added in on each check as a standard policy. I asked about the smell and she said no one else had complained and asked did I still smell it. She said the waitress had told her that I had said something but she had no one else complain. I enjoyed the food but the experience was completely soured by the gratuity farce and then the lack of response to the strong odor. We did enjoy the food ...

I am local and go here all the time. The staff is efficient and nice, service is fast and food is tasty. Green curry and pad Thai are really good. Most importantly for a Hawaiian restaurant - this place has consistent quality.

When you're walking around Honolulu at night looking for a Thai spot, then finding yourself at Siam Square is a good thing.  The place is on the 2nd floor, and is unpretentious.  It may look like a tourist trap, seeing as its above an ABC store, but trust me, it is legit, Mr and Mrs Tourist.  Because I've never tried it, the green curry was ordered, along with brown rice.  Once it arrived, and my curry professional plated it for me, I dug in with my chop sticks.  I dont know if it was the heat wave, or the high methane content of my shared hostel room, but time felt like it paused for a moment, as the nuttiness of the rice danced with the delicious aroma and coconut'y spice, all the way down my esophageal into my duodenum.  Props, Siam Square... you got mad street cred
